ook, Julia Elsky argues that these writers reexamined both their Jewishness and their place as authors in France through the language in which they wrote. The group of authors Elsky considers depicted key moments in the war from their perspective as Jewish émigrés, including the June 1940 civilian flight from Paris, life in the occupied and southern zones, the roundups and internment camps, and the Resistance in France and in London. Writing in French, they expressed multiple cultural, religious, and linguistic identities, challenging the boundaries between center and periphery, between French and foreign, even when their sense of belonging was being violently denied.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aFrench languagexPolitical aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aFrench literaturexJewish authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aFrench literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aJewish authorszFrancexLanguagexHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zFrancexLiterature and the war. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh  aFrancophonie.  aFrench literature.  aHolocaust.  aJewish writers.  aOccupied France.  aResistance.  aShoah.  aVichy.  abilingualism.  amultilingualism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069218140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503614369zCo-access DOI >> click Walter 